## **00:00-09:00: The Shadowy EU Institution and the "Before and After" Moment**

Mercouris frames the current situation as a historic inflection point marking a clear "before and after" divide. The catalyst is a controversial decision by the EU''s Council of Representatives—an institution he refers to as **"Korea"** (from its French acronym). He emphasizes this body''s shadowy, underreported nature, noting it receives "practically none" of the media attention given to the European Commission or Parliament, yet produces "the bulk of EU legislation" through regular votes on resolutions and directives.

He recounts a revealing 2015 scandal when Greece''s new Syriza government discovered their representative at Korea had supposedly voted for Russian sanctions they never authorized. When Greek officials protested, they faced immediate retaliation: investigations into their Russian ties and coordinated media attacks. Since then, Greece has never again objected to Korea decisions, illustrating the institution''s coercive power.

The current decision, passed by majority vote rather than unanimity, fundamentally alters the legal status of approximately €140 billion in frozen Russian central bank assets. Previously requiring renewal every six months, the freeze is now indefinite—effectively permanent. Mercouris notes he cannot identify which states voted how, as Korea''s opacity makes tracking votes difficult even for dedicated researchers.

